Myself Darshan Madhukar Mahajan, BFA in drawing and painting, postgraduate diploma in Indian aesthetic and Comparative mythology.
My interest lies in mythology, legends and folklores from all over the world. Analysis and theoretical aspects while studying these myths and tales influenced me a lot. Theories of various scholars helped me understand why and how myths or tales are created around the world, how it shapes society and people. Understanding these theories made me appreciate the connection between society, myths and rituals and gave a great understanding and increased acceptance towards everything. The narrative patterns and metaphors, anthropomorphic characters, human behaviour and many more elements attract my attention.  This helps me to construct the hypothesis and further formulates my research. I also try to express this in my artworks too.

fields.content:
Portrayal of the Elephant King Chhadanta

 

The surviving remains of Indian art cover a period of more than two thousand years. During this time many school of thought have flourished and decayed, invaders of many races have poured in to India and contributed to the infinite variety of her intellectual resources ; countless dynasties have ruled and passed away ; and so we do not wonder that many varieties of artistic expression remain, to record for us, in a language of their own. Just as through all Indian schools of thought there runs like a golden thread the fundamental idealism of Upanishads, the Vedanta, so in all Indian art there is a unity that underlies all its different variety.[1]  Indian Art has its own style of narration of its own literature. Narration is in form of stories, poetry, dance, drama, paintings, sculpture etc. Indian narrative materials on which this paintings, sculpture, poetry are based on the mythological stories, depicting daily chores, also showing the cultural locality, tradition etc. Just as in poetry in the paintings to these narrative material were artistically refined and just like poetry the art of paintings created clichés, on which the individual design of each artist are based on. The pictorial description needs just a few clichés to explain the scene in the paintings and events taking place in them to anyone familiar with pictorial language. For one who is completely unfamiliar with it requires written or verbal explanation, just as one unaware of language of poetry needs commentary.[2]

The earliest paintings in India have been found in primitive caves and rock shelters. These paintings were mainly based on hunting scenes representing man in his encounter with wild animals.2 whereas the earliest historical paintings in India belong to the Satvahana period. The Satvahana were the most dominant power in the Deccan from the 2nd century B.C. to the 2nd century A.D. During the time of these monarchs, some of the most glorious Buddhist caves were excavated in living rocks. Mostly they were located in the western part of India that is Nasik, Bedsa, Bhaja, Karla, Kondane caves. The earliest caves at Ajanta are also from the Satvahana period. The fresco paintings of this period at Ajanta finely cover the walls, pillars and celling. Mostly this cave illustrates the scene from life of the Buddha and his previous lives as depicted in Jataka and Avadanas. The caves at Ajanta are covered with the depiction of floral, animal and decorative motifs.[3]  The Ajanta Satvahana period was followed by the Vakataka period. The Vakataka are first mentioned in inscriptions of 2nd century A.D. from Amravati. Some of the caves at Ajanta have inscriptions of the Vakataka period. The caves with more elaborated pillars and capitals are of the Vakataka period. It’s mainly the decorative element, chiefly composed of pearls and ribbons, so characteristic of the Vakataka age. This period tradition as seen at Ajanta is derived from earlier Satvahana. There are excellent illustrations in these paintings at Ajanta of six limbs of paintings, shadanga, composed of rupabheda, variety of form, pramana, proper proportion, bhava, depiction of emotion, lavanya yojana, infusion of grace, sadrishya, likeness and varnika bhanga, mixing of colours to produce a visual depth in the paintings. The diversity of form is indeed incredible. The artists have excellently painted a vast complex of human, animals and plant forms creating a drama. The artist at Ajanta has control over not only proportions of individual figures but also have ability to compose them.[4] Thus these frescos at Ajanta are also called as highly sophisticated art. The connection between the painting and dramatic technique is as close as that between the painting and the literature.[5]

The narrative material on which the paintings at Ajanta belong in a superficial Buddhist revision. Artist depicts the hunting adventures, as well as travel adventures and even romantic scene. Also stories giving examples for both clever and ethical behaviour in general and especially on affairs of state and last but not the least Jataka tales. Caves are painted at all is due to the fact that sponsor who favour Buddhism wished to give monks the opportunity to impart their teaching to visitors of monasteries through the pictorial walls as well as through words. This purpose of monastery painting implicate that the theme of paintings were revised in Buddhist spirit and some were invented by the monk itself.[6] Thus the wall paintings mostly of Jataka stories are the pictorial sermon which imparts various teachings or parimitas by Buddha. There are around 550 Jataka tales that describes the event and pervious birth of Buddha, sometimes animal, sometimes as a human.[7] Many of the tales from Jataka are artistically composed on wall. As we know Jataka are stories about one of the incarnation of Buddha prior to his birth as prince Siddhartha, son of king Suddhodara and queen Maya. Jataka were extensively used to proclaim the massage of Buddha to the pilgrims. So the monks and the painted stone walls narrate the life and teaching of Buddha as in chhadanta Jataka, guru Jataka, kapi Jataka and lot more.[8] One of the interesting pictorial narrations of Jataka tale can be seen twice in Ajanta of Chhadanta Jataka. Chhadanta Jataka has several versions of stories. Where Chhadanta literally mean six tusks or six teeth. This story mainly depicts the Dana parimita of the bodhisattva. The most common narration of this Jataka is like:-

Figure 1 – Chhadanta Jataka Cave No 17

“ Far away in the Himalaya on blue waters of Chhadantadaho lake, protected by the seven rock ranges, in a deep cave, dwelt bodhisattva, king of 8000 Chhadanta elephant with his two elephant queen. It chanced on a day that two queen were standing under a large banyan tree, which the king having shaken, Mahasubhadra , the elder, was showered over with golden dust from the flowers while on Challusubhadra, the younger, fell dry sticks, leaves and ants. Jealousy of Mahasubhadra, and hatred of the king filled chullasubhadra’s breast and she prayed that in her next birth she might become Subadra, daughter of king of Madu and wed the king of Banares. Him she would beguile in to sending a hunter to slay the king of elephants, conspicuous from his white body, red mouth and feet, and six tusks and killed herself and was born as she wished to be. She remembered her old jealousy and in due time the royal hunter Sonuttara was sent to kill the king of elephants, Subadra giving him full directions as to the route he should follow the suvarna hills, above the Chhadantadaho lake. Whence the Sonuttara would easily recognise the great white king. Surrounded by his herd of elephants, under the spreading banyan tree. From his rocky height he observed the king going daily after bathing, to a retired spot and here the hunter dug a pit and wrapping himself in a saffron robe of a priest, waited for favourable moment and shot who sought to pacify him by spreading the sacred robe over his trunk. Questioning the hunter, the bodhisattva ascertains that he is doing subhadra’s bidding, where upon he cuts off his tusk himself and offers them in his trunks. The hunter returned from his murderous errand; and laying the tusk before the queen he said ‘Respected queen, in your previous birth having cherished hatred against your husband the king of the Chhadanta elephant you wished to kill him. Accordingly I have killed him and here are his tusks.’ The queen filled with remorse for her cruel deed in causing the death of such a noble animal, she died the same day of a broken heart.”[9]

Figure 2 – Detail drawing of the mural of Chhadanta Jataka from Cave No 17

The visual narration of this Chhadanta Jataka is painted in two caves, cave no. 10 and cave no. 17. The painting in cave 17 has a different narrative pattern. The mural is damaged and remained in fragments.[10] This Chhadanta Jataka mural is located at the left side of the entrance door of cave 17. The size of the mural is around 10ft. 3in. by 10ft. 3in. The pictorial narrative pattern is aligned or ordered. It seems to be scattered in a way. The artist had made changes as per the space. One without knowing the Jataka cannot identify the visual narration of the tale. Taking sense in order in which they occur in the story, the Chhadanta elephants are shown in the lower part of the composition among the lotus plants and other tropical vegetation. Number of ants is shown climbing the stem. Two hill people, a man and a woman are up in the rocks, the man carries a bow and arrows in his right hand, and dagger in his waist-belt, woman has three rows of beads round the waist, to which a bunch of leaves is attached, watching the white elephant below, on the back of which a wolf has leapt. To the right two black faced monkeys (langur) and below them two vultures sit on the rocks.[11] Which shows that the inhabitants of jungle watch a wolf and vultures near the queen elephant Challusubhadra, who leapt down from the rocks to her death.[12] At the top left-hand corner, the king is shown seated on a couch, which his queen reclining against him. Both appear happy. Two men approach them on their knees, which seem to have brought news of importance probably of the Chhadanta elephant. At the top centre of the picture a man is shown in act of discharging his bow at the elephant below.[13] In the top right corner, a seated devotee with an elephant is shown; whose trunk is raised may be Challusubhadra worshipping a prateyka Buddha in the mountains to ensure herself a good incarnation.[14] In the right centre of the picture stands the huge white elephant king, Chhadanta, with only one tusk, upon which he rests his trunk under a jewelled tree, while a man, hunter kneels and makes profound obeisance before him. The same hunter is shown carry away the tusks, slung on sticks across their shoulders. He is the hunter of the legend, and from his dress and short spares beards, looks like the jungle man. Above it is a herd of elephants, both large and small, in a state of great excitement. To the left is the final scene of this visual Jataka story. In a pavilion of the palace, the king sits on a couch, and supports the queen, who stricken with remorse , in causing, as she imagined, the death of the elephant king Chhadanta, mourns in her husband’s arms. A dark skinned female attendant looks wistfully in to her face; while beside, others are engaged in fanning and using fly flap. At the foot of the couch, a woman kneels and brushes the queen’s feet with a lotus flower, while another is engaged in picking rice, as she has before the common bamboo winnowing basket used by natives for cleaning grain. Above, a servant, in a white tunic bound round the waist with a belt, enters with a tray containing the two elephant tusk, which he is about to present to the queen. Two men behind are engaged in conversation. The upper part of the pavilion is richly decorated by festoons.[15]

Although the visual narration has many changes in the story than that of the real Jataka story, still it completely narrates the story of elephant king Chhadanta showing his greatness and teaching of the bodhisattva of Dana parimita. The visual narrative compositions are scattered on the wall but it still justice to the story. The repetition of the characters helps in the narration. The viewer can completely understand the Jataka painting of king Chhadanta with the verbal interpretations. The painting style and the compositions with the shadanga make the painting more beautiful. Various scenes in the painting generate a curiosity in viewer about the story and starts composing the Jataka with the repetitive forms and figures. Although the Chhadanta king is with two tusks his greatness is shown using the semi-realistic herd of elephants and jewelled tree behind him showing the vegetation of the jungle. The hunter is shown in various actions firstly he kneels down before the elephant king, then casts a reverent glance at the elephant and lastly goes to the royal court with tusks, this shows the repetition of the hunter in the painting like in the story board. So the visual narration and composition of the mural painting in cave no. 17 of one of the birth of Buddha as Chhadanta king completely narrates the story in a very alluring way.

The Ellora caves, locally known as ‘Verul Leni’ is located in Aurangabad- Chalisgaon road at a distance of 30 km north-northwest of Aurangabad. The name Ellora itself inspires everyone as it represents one of the largest rock-hewn monastic-temple complexes in the entire world. Ellora is also world famous for the largest single monolithic excavation in the world. The caves are hewn out of the volcanic basaltic formation of Maharasthra, known as ‘Deccan Trap’, the term trap being of Scandinavian origin representing the step like formation of the volcanic deposits. The rock formation, on weathering has given rise to the appearance of terraces with flat summits. At Ellora, one can also have a glimpse of the channels (near Cave 32) through which the volcanic lava once flowed. These channels, due to overheating, have the characteristic brownish red colour.[1]

Figure 1: Cave 15 of Ellora caves

     Cave 15 is known as Dashavatara Cave belongs to the period of Rashtrakuta king, Dantidurga. This cave mainly depicts Lord Shiva & Lord Vishnu in various forms. This two-storeyed structure has a large courtyard in which stands a monolithic Nandi mandapa. River goddesses flank the entrance. Earlier it was a Buddhist monastery but it was converted into a Shiva temple in the 8th century AD. The cave is of two stories, the lower being a few feet above the level of the court, and supported by fourteen square pillars and measuring 95 feet in length. In the left end of the front aisle, the stair ascends and is lighted by a window at the landing, where it turns to the right. On the wall of this landing are eleven compartments, each about two feet in height, with bas-reliefs. Another flight of steps leads to the end of the front aisle of the great hall above, 95 feet wide and 110 feet deep inclusive of the vestibule of the shrine, supported by 44 square columns, including the two in front of the vestibule. [2]

     Here, one can see some Buddha sculptures on the capitals of the first floor. The first storey is reached by a flight of steps, which has eleven sunken compartments in which huge bas-reliefs of various gods and goddesses are carved. They are Ganapathi, Parvati, Surya, Siva and Parvati, Mahisasuramardini, Ardhanareeshwara, Bhavani or Durga, Uma in penance attitude, and Kali. The second storey measures 109 feet by 95 feet inclusive of a shrine of linga and an antechamber. The walls on both sides of the hall are divided into six cells each. The cells on the north side show images of dancing Siva, a pitha for linga, Siva Parvati playing chausar, and Ravana shaking the Kailasa. Markandeya-anugraha and Gangadhara are depicted on two panels to the north of the entrance to the vestibule. The south wall has the representations of Govardhanadhari Vishnu, Sheshasayi Vishnu, Vishnu on garuda, Varaha, the boar incarnation of Vishnu, Vamana avatara of Vishnu, Narasimha avatara of Vishnu. Narasimha, or the man lion form of Vishnu, wrestling with his enemy who looks defeated before the four armed Vishnu. Tripurantaka and Lingodbhava are depicted on two panels to the south of the entrance.[3]

One of the most important aspects of the history of visual art is printmaking. The Stoneage man-made an impression of his hands on the walls of caves and started the journey of visual art which is still going on.

     My art journey started with my travel to the city from my village in search of art education. This was because art education was available only in megacities. When I came to Sir JJ School of arts, Mumbai, I got to know the wide spectrum of mediums of visual arts. During my bachelor's degree in fine arts, Printmaking was one of the subjects along with others. I got fascinated by the medium and started working in it with dedication. Seeing my progress in the medium, my professor Nikam sir selected me for the National Paper Making Camp in Kerala. During the camp, I understood the making and the importance of "Paper". Paper is the most important element in the field of art as it is widely used as a surface for the creation of art. The papermaking process started to answer the questions I had been asking. The first question was, " How will I work in this field in the future? " Due to the financial difficulties, I had to work hard for survival. The second question was, " How to continue art practice with less material ?". This was because large works required a lot of money. And the third question was, " How to continue printmaking if the press is not available after college? ". I got answers to all the above while learning the process of papermaking.

     I am now studying an MFA and working on print and pulp print. I chose Pulp print and Printmaking for this dissertation to study more about the process. Therefore, I have tried to bring to light the important parts of the history of papermaking. For example, the first paper was made in China, then when was the first paper made in India? Then what is the process of papermaking and how to extend the life of paper and artwork to make pulp print? The different types of pulps that can be used to make paper. Also, I have made an attempt to understand the background of artwork of the artist who contributed to papermaking and pulp print in the Indian Art world

After the paper technology reached the Arabs, the Arabians improved the technique and supplemented linen with flax and other vegetable fibres. With the conquest of Sind by the Arabs, Khurasani paper was first introduced in India early in the eighth century AD, and it continued to be imported for several centuries.

     The reference to Indian paper suggests that the paper-making industry, however limited, had already been established in India, most probably in Delhi and Lahore, the two chief political and cultural seats of the Sultanate period.

     In India, the first paper industry was developed in Kashmir, established by Sultan Zainul Abedin (Shahi Khan) of Kashmir in 1417-67 AD.

     In India, the available writing materials were generally of two types: hard and soft. Stone, metal, shells and earthenware were examples of hard material. Engraving, embossing, painting and scratching were used for writing. Soft materials were wooden board (pati), dust (dhuli), birch-bark (bhurja-patra), palm-leaves (tada-patra), leather (ajina), cotton cloths (karpasika pata) and paper.

     Paper:- Paper, as a writing material, was hardly known in India before the 11th century AD. Al-Biruni writes, "it was in China that paper was first manufactured, Chinese prisoners introduced the fabrication of paper in Samarkand, and thereupon it was made in various places, so as to meet the existing want".

     In India paper was mainly used by the Government for state records, by priests for religious books, and by moneylenders and traders for account books.

     The handmade glazed paper was a remarkable product of medieval India. Bark and leaves of trees, silk or cotton clothes, planks, leather and parchment formed this paper. This paper was not only used in India but also exported to other countries. But nowadays the handmade paper industry is declining rapidly. Only a few areas are still there which produce a handmade quality paper.

The history of paper dates back almost 2,000 years to when inventors in China first crafted cloth sheets to record their drawings and writings. Before then, people communicated through pictures and symbols etched on stone, bones, cave walls, or clay tablets.

     paper_historyPaper, as we know it today, was first made in Lei-Yang, China by Ts'ai Lun, a Chinese court official. In all likelihood, Ts'ai mixed mulberry bark, hemp and rags with water, mashed it into pulp, pressed out the liquid and hung the thin mat to dry in the sun. During the 8th century, Muslims (from the region that is now Syria, Saudi Arabia, and Iraq) learned the Chinese secret of papermaking when they captured a Chinese paper mill. Later, when the Muslims invaded Europe, they brought this secret with them. The first paper mill was built in Spain, and soon, the paper was being made at mills all across Europe. Over the next 800 years, the paper was used for printing important books, bibles, and legal documents. England began making large supplies of paper in the late 15th century and supplied the colonies with paper for many years. Finally, in 1690, the first U.S. paper mill was built in Pennsylvania.

     At first, American paper mills used the Chinese method of shredding old rags and clothes into individual fibres to make paper. As the demand for paper grew, the mills changed used fibre from trees because the wood was less expensive and more abundant than cloth.

    Today, paper is made from trees mostly grown on working forests and from recovered paper. Recycling has always been a part of papermaking. When you recycle your used paper, paper mills will use it to make new newspapers, notebook paper, paper grocery bags, corrugated boxes, envelopes, magazines, cartons, and other paper products.

     Besides using recovered paper and trees to make paper, paper mills may also use wood chips and sawdust left over from lumber operations (whose products are used to make houses, furniture, and other things). Today, more than 36 percent of the fibre used to make new paper products in the United States comes from recycled sources.

Any natural material composed of cellulose and capable of being reduced to pulp-like consistency can be considered as appropriate material for experimentation, including Cotton, Jute, Hemp, Straw, Bamboo leaves & twigs, Coarse grasses, Banana stem, Hibiscus, Cabbage stumps, Mulberry, Cornstalks, Sugarcane, Goldrols leaves, Flax, Nettle, etc

 

 

 

Identification

 

The part of the plant which can be used for making paper as identified according to its fibre type in the following manner:

 

1. Fruit seed hair - example: cotton

2. Bast/ Inner Bark/ Phleom - example : banana,hemp,jute,flax

3. Leaf - example: bamboo, gladiolas

4. Grass - example: sedge, reeds

5. Stem structure - example: bamboo, mulberry

प्लेटोच्या म्हणण्यानुसार, “सौंदर्य” ही एक कल्पना किंवा स्वरूप होते ज्याचा परिणाम सुंदर गोष्टी होय.

          तुलनात्मकतेने “सौंदर्य” सुगम वस्तूंच्या गाभ्यामध्ये सुरू होते, कारण तो सौंदर्याचा एक प्रकार आहे. सर्वात महत्त्वाचा प्रश्न: या सर्व सुंदर गोष्टींमध्ये काय साम्य आहे ?. ते जाणून घेणे म्हणजे “सौंदर्य” जाणून घेणे.

                    आकाराच्या सिद्धांतानुसार वास्तविकतेचे दोन भिन्न स्तर अस्तित्त्वात आहेत. आपण ज्या ठिकाणी आहोत त्यात दृष्टी आणि ध्वनीचे दृश्यमान जग आणि दृश्यमान जगाच्या वर उभे असलेले आणि आकार देण्याकरिता सुगम जग आहेत.  उदाहरणार्थ, प्लेटो म्हणतो की एक सुंदर व्यक्ती किंवा एखादे सुंदर चित्र ओळखण्यास सक्षम होण्याव्यतिरिक्त, आपल्याकडे देखील सौंदर्याची सामान्य कल्पना आहे आणि आपण एखाद्या व्यक्तीमध्ये किंवा एका चित्रातले “सौंदर्य” ओळखू शकतो कारण आपल्याकडे अमूर्तामध्ये “सौंदर्य” संकल्पना आहे.  दुसऱ्या शब्दांत, ज्या सुंदर गोष्टी आपण पहातो त्या केवळ सुंदरच आहेत कारण त्या सौंदर्याच्या अधिक सामान्य प्रकारात भाग घेतात. हे “सौंदर्य” अदृश्य, चिरंतन आणि अपरिवर्तनीय स्वरूपाचे आहे, दृश्यमान जगाच्या गोष्टी जुन्या वृद्ध होऊ शकतात आणि त्यांचे “सौंदर्य” गमावू शकतात. प्रेम, प्रतिसाद “सौंदर्य” आणि इच्छा आहे, परंतु आकार,क्षेत्र “सौंदर्य” स्वतः शोधून काढते. आकाराच्या सहभागात विशिष्ट वस्तू “सौंदर्य” शोधून काढते.   प्लेटो सिम्पोजियममध्ये , सॉक्रेटिस दावा करतो की “सौंदर्य” हे एका शरीरापासून ते सर्वापर्यंत शुद्ध सौंदर्याकडे, नंतर सर्व सुंदर आत्म्यांद्वारे, कायद्यांद्वारे आणि ज्ञानाच्या प्रकारांद्वारे आत्म्याच्या सौंदर्यावर पोहचण्यासाठी आत्म्याची प्रगती कारणीभूत ठरते.

          एखाद्या व्यक्तीस विशिष्ट प्रकारचे “सौंदर्य” प्रेमापासून तर स्वतःच प्रेमळ सौंदर्याकडे जाणे शक्य आहे, ज्यामधून सर्व सुंदर गोष्टी त्यांचे स्वरूप प्राप्त करतात. या सौंदर्याकडे डोळेझाक करून आणि त्याचा पाठपुरावा करणे हे जगण्याचे सर्वोत्तम उदाहरण आहे.तो विशिष्ट शरीरांवर प्रेम करून, तिथून सामान्यत: शरीरात, विशिष्ट मनांमध्ये, सर्वसाधारणपणे मनामध्ये, कायद्यांकडे व व्यवहारांकडे, ज्ञानाकडे आणि शेवटी “सौंदर्य” स्वरूपाच्या ज्ञानाकडे जाऊ लागला. चढाव वाढत्या सामान्यीकरणांपैकी एक आहे जिथे एखाद्याच्या सौंदर्यावरचे प्रेम अधिकाधिक गोष्टी स्वीकारते.

          शेवटी, एखाद्याच्या सौंदर्यावरचे प्रेम केवळ एका गोष्टीस, सौंदर्याचे रूप स्वीकारेल, परंतु या स्वरूपात ते सर्व सुंदर आहे हे ओळखेल. 

          “सौंदर्य” काय असू शकते याची एक भावना याशिवाय आहे: मोजमाप आणि प्रमाण चिन्हे त्याची उपस्थिती दर्शवितात आणि याचा चांगुलपणा आणि न्यायाशी संबंध आहे.

इथल्या सौंदर्याची कल्पना संपूर्ण ऐक्य म्हणून किंवा खरोखरच एकतेच्या तत्त्वाप्रमाणे केलेली आहे. 

प्लेटोची “सौंदर्य” विषयक विचार असे म्हणतात की “सौंदर्य” एक उद्देश गुणवत्ता आहे जी कमीतकमी तीव्र आणि अनुक्रमे सुंदर किंवा कमी सुंदर वस्तूंनी उदाहरणे दिली आहे. जाणकारांशी ऑब्जेक्टच्या नात्याशी किंवा त्याच्या समाप्तीसाठी एक साधन म्हणून स्वतंत्रपणे “सौंदर्य” अस्तित्वात आहे.

सुंदर, मग ते काय आहे याची पर्वा न करता स्वतःच एक वस्तू म्हणून अस्तित्वात आहे, सुंदर वस्तूंच्या संबंधात स्वतंत्र आणि सर्वोच्च आहे जे त्याच्या अस्तित्वातून काही प्रमाणात सामायिक करून सुंदर आहे. 

          एका सुंदर ऑब्जेक्टसाठी मूळ आणि बाह्य असे काहीतरी आहे. तिचे “सौंदर्य” तेथे जाणकारांपेक्षा स्वतंत्रपणे आहे आणि ते सुंदर आहे की नाही हे वैयक्तिक मूल्यांकनांवर अवलंबून नाही. प्लेटोच्या कल्पनांना प्रचलित शास्त्रीय संकल्पनेचा नमुना मानले जाऊ शकते. त्यानुसार  सौंदर्यात क्रम, प्रमाण आणि सममितीनुसार सुसंगत भागांमध्ये अखंड भागांची व्यवस्था असते. प्लटो सौंदर्याच्या विचारांत मानत असे की, त्या पाहणाऱ्याच्या प्रतिसादात स्थानिकीकरण झाले नाही .  प्लेटोच्या सिद्धांत असूनही आश्चर्य वाटले पाहिजे की “सौंदर्य” गुणवत्ता ओळखण्यायोग्य आहे की नाही.

         दुसऱ्या शब्दांत, “सौंदर्य” हे एक सापेक्ष मूल्यांकन आहे, जे पाहणाऱ्याच्या डोळ्यात आहे,जर आपला असा विश्वास असेल तर आपण असा निष्कर्ष काढला पाहिजे की “सौंदर्य” एका व्यक्तिनिष्ठ निर्णयाद्वारे तयार केले गेले आहे, ज्यात प्रत्येक व्यक्ती काहीतरी सुंदर आहे की नाही हे निर्धारित करते.  “सौंदर्य” हा एक नमुना किंवा स्वरूप आहे ज्यामधून सर्व सुंदर गोष्टी व्युत्पन्न केल्या आहेत, तर असेही मानत आहोत की “सौंदर्य” एक वस्तुनिष्ठ वैशिष्ट्य आहे.

         “सौंदर्य” संपूर्णपणे व्यक्तिनिष्ठ असू शकत नाही — म्हणजेच, कोणालाही जे काही सुंदर वाटेल किंवा ते सुंदर असेल तर त्या शब्दाला काहीच अर्थ नाही, किंवा आपण एखाद्या सुंदर गोष्टीला मान्यता दिल्याशिवाय आपण काहीही संवाद करीत नाही असे दिसते. त्यास वैयक्तिक वृत्ती म्हणता येईल.याव्यतिरिक्त, विशिष्ट न्यायालयात भिन्न व्यक्ती नक्कीच भिन्न असू शकतात, परंतु हे देखील स्पष्ट आहे की आपले निर्णय काही प्रमाणात एकसारखे असतात.

कोणत्याही प्रकारे, आपण नक्कीच सांगू शकतो की जर शरीर सममित आणि प्रमाणात असेल तर दुसर्‍याच्या शरीरावर आपले आकर्षण वाढते. या अर्थाने, सौंदर्यासाठी काही विशिष्ट “सौंदर्य” वैशिष्ट्ये आहेत. शास्त्रज्ञांचा असा विश्वास आहे की आपणाला  प्रमाणित शरीर अधिक निरोगी असल्याचे समजते. हे खालील प्रसिद्ध प्रतिमेत सूचित केले आहे जे चौरस आणि मंडळामध्ये एक आदर्श मानवी शरीर दर्शविते.

          “सौंदर्य” स्वत: च्या पलीकडे विस्तारित मार्गाने परिभाषित केल्याचा दावा करतो. हे ओळखणे आवश्यक आहे. अशा प्रकारे, कल्पनांच्या या क्रमानुसार आपण विचार करू शकतो की “सौंदर्य” व सौंदर्याचा अनुभव घेण्याचा एक अस्तित्वात्मक मार्ग आहे. जे पाहतो त्यावर आक्षेप घेण्याकडे कल असतो. निःसंशयपणे, असे काही व्यक्तिनिष्ठ घटक आहेत जे आपल्याला “सौंदर्य” परिभाषित करण्यास मदत करतात. दुसरीकडे, एखादी विशिष्ट सामान्य आणि सार्वत्रिक वैशिष्ट्ये “सौंदर्य” कल्पनेशी जोडलेली आहेत हे नाकारता येत नाही. म्हणून आणि आलंकारिक भाषेत सांगायचे तर मला विश्वास आहे की “सौंदर्य” ही एकसूरी संकल्पना असेल जी मुख्यतः वस्तुनिष्ठ आणि अंतर्देशीय परिवर्तनांद्वारे तयार केली जाते, जी वेळ आणि संदर्भानुसार बदलू शकते.

मानवी भावना या विचारांवर अवलंबून आहेत. विचार हे आपल्या अनुभवांपासून, घडणाऱ्या घटनांपासून तयार किंवा प्रगत होतात. या घटना समजण्यासाठी अनुभवण्यासाठी आपणास इंद्रियांची आवश्यकता असते. परंतू यात सर्वांत जलद कोणता अनुभव येत असेल तर तो दृक अनुभव होय. चित्रपट,छायाचित्र,एखादा प्रसंग याचा प्रथम दृक अनुभव आपणास येतो. या सर्व क्रियेची पडताळणी आपली बुद्धी इंद्रियांद्वारे होते.

          मनुष्य प्रत्येक घटनेत किंवा अनुभवात पडताळणी करणे अनिवार्य समजायला लागतो व त्याची समज त्याला त्या अनुभवाच्या गाभ्यापर्यंत घेऊन जाण्याचा प्रयत्न करते. थोडक्यात त्याला त्याला त्या अनुभवास पूर्णत्वाला घेऊन जायचे असते. या सर्व चढाओढीत त्या अनुभवाचा आस्वाद घेण्याचा विचार बाजूला राहून जातो. या पूर्णत्वाची शर्यत आस्वादास निर्जीव बनवते का? या प्रश्नाचे स्पष्टीकरण माझ्या प्रबंधाचा विषय आहे.

          प्रागैतिहासिक काळापासून मानवाने संवाद साधण्यासाठी दृक माध्यमाचा वापर केला आहे. माहितीचा साठा करण्यासाठी सुध्दा दृक माध्यमांचा वापर केला गेला आहे. गुहाचित्रे, लेण्या, चित्रलिपी इ. मधून आपणास त्याची प्रचिती येते.  इ.स.पु. ७०००० ते इ.स.पु. १०००० या काळात दैनंदीन जीवन जसे पुजाअर्चा, शिकार इ. विषय चित्र स्वरूपात त्या काळातील संस्कृतीचे दर्शन घडवतात. पिढ्यानपिढ्या जपलेली ज्ञानाची ही संपत्ती साधनसमुग्रीचा अभाव असूनही जतन केली गेली. फ्रान्समधील लास्को येथील गुहांमध्ये अनेक तऱ्हेची प्राण्यांची चित्रे दिसतात.  भिंतींवर व छतांवर ही चित्रे रेखाटलेली आहेत. संशोधनकर्त्यांनुसार ही चित्रे बायसन, हरीण, घोडे त्यासोबत कळप व शिकार इ. विषयांवरील आहेत. माती, कोळसा, राख, प्राण्यांचे रक्त या गोष्टींचा वापर करून चित्रानिर्मिती केली गेली. ही चित्रे वास्तविक चित्राच्या मुलतत्वांचे पालन करत नाहीत. उदा. शरीरशास्त्र, रंगछटा, त्रिमितीय आभास या तत्वांचा अविर्भाव या चित्रांमध्ये नाही तरीही आपणास शिकार, पूजा-हवन, बळी इ. प्रसंग सहज लक्षात येतात. या प्रसंगांमध्ये मानवी देहाचेही रेखाटन केले आहे. काही रेषांच्या साहाय्याने, सांकेतिकरित्या मानवी प्रतिमा रेखाटलेल्या आहेत. हीच चित्रे आज अभिजतपणा व कलस्वादाची जननी समजली गेली आहेत.

          इ.स.पु. ३००० ते इ.स.पु. १००० या काळात नाईल नदीच्या खोऱ्यात बहरलेली इजिप्तची कलसंस्कृती ही अनन्यसाधारण आहे. इजिप्तमध्ये मरणोत्तर जीवनाची संकल्पना होती. तेथील कलेला धार्मिक स्वरूप प्राप्त झाले. येथील कलानिर्मितितील महत्वाचा पैलू म्हणजे चित्रालिपी होय. मनुष्याच्या दैनंदिन गोष्टी, ऋतु, शक्ती, पंचमहाभूते, सूर्य, चंद्र, भाले, चाबूक इ. गोष्टींचे सहज स्वरूप या चित्रलिपीत पाहायला मिळते. इजिप्शियन मूर्तिकलाही पुरातन कलेपेक्षा प्रगत जाणवते. दगडामध्ये कोरीव काम करून अनेक भव्य कलाकृती शिल्प साकारण्यात आली.

          ऐतिहासिक पाठपुरावा आणि चित्रकलेचा अभ्यास करताना “सहजता” ही चित्राची आत्मा आहे असे कळते. अकॅडमीक शिक्षणातही याचा अनुभव येतो. परंतु चित्रातील “सौंदर्य” व पूर्णत्व जाणून घेण्यासाठी आपणास अनेक विचारवंतांचे विचार समजून घ्यावे लागतील.

ऋणनिर्देश

          शैक्षणिक वर्ष २०१९-२०२० रेखा व रंगकला, अंतीम वर्ष मधील “सहजतेतील “सौंदर्य” आणि अपूर्णतेतील पूर्णत्व” हा माझ्या प्रबंधाचा विषय असून हा एक अभ्यासपूर्ण अनुभव ठरला. या प्रबंधाच्या अभ्यासात व माहितीसंपादनात “प्रा.श्री.विजय बोंदर” यांचे मोलाचे मार्गदर्शन मिळाले, आणि निष्कर्षापर्यंत पोहचण्यात मदत मिळाली. प्रत्यक्षरित्या आणि अप्रत्यक्षरीत्या मला अनेक जणांचे सहकार्य मिळाले, त्या सर्व सहकाऱ्यांचे मी ऋण व्यक्त करतो. या सहकार्याशिवाय हा प्रबंध होणे कठीण होते.

समक्रमण (सिनेटिक्स) ही एक समस्या सोडविण्याची पद्धत आहे जी विचार करण्याच्या प्रक्रियेस उत्तेजित करते ज्याचा विषय नकळत असू शकतो. ही पद्धत जॉर्ज एम. प्रिन्स (५ एप्रिल १९१८ - ९ जून २००९) विकसित केली गेली.

          गॉर्डन आणि प्रिन्स यांनी त्यांचा सराव आणि त्यांची नवीन कंपनी सिनेटिक्स या दोहोंची नावे दिली आहेत ज्यामुळे कंपनीचा भाग नसलेले लोक प्रशिक्षित असतात आणि या सरावाचा वापर करतात म्हणून गोंधळ होऊ शकतो. हे नाव ट्रेडमार्क केलेले असताना, गटांमध्ये सर्जनशील समस्येचे निराकरण करण्यासाठी हा एक मानक शब्द बनला आहे. 

                                समक्रमण हा तर्कसंगत मार्गाने सर्जनशीलता आणि समस्येचे निराकरण करण्याचा एक मार्ग आहे. "पारंपारिकपणे, वस्तुस्थितीनंतर सर्जनशील प्रक्रियेचा विचार केला गेला आहे . समक्रमण अभ्यासानुसार व्हिव्होमध्ये सर्जनशील प्रक्रियेचा शोध घेण्याचा प्रयत्न केला गेला आहे." 

गॉर्डनच्या म्हणण्यानुसार, समक्रमणाच्या संशोधनात तीन मुख्य धारणा आहेत.

          या गृहितकांना ध्यानात घेऊन समक्रमणाचा असा विश्वास आहे की सर्जनशीलता कशी कार्य करते हे जर त्यांना समजले असेल तर लोक सर्जनशील बनण्यात अधिक चांगले असू शकतात.

          सर्जनशीलतेतील एक महत्त्वाचा घटक म्हणजे  अप्रसंगिक घटना . एखाद्या समस्येचे किंवा कल्पनांचे भावनिक आणि असमंजसपणाचे घटक समजून घेतल्यास, एखादा प्रश्न समस्येचे निराकरण करण्यात अधिक यशस्वी होऊ शकतो. 

संशोधनामध्ये प्रतिबंध कमी करण्यात आणि प्रत्येकाची अंतर्निहित सर्जनशीलता मुक्त करण्यात सर्जनशील वर्तनाचे महत्त्व यावर जोर दिला . गॉर्डनने आणि त्याच्या सहकार्‍यांनी विशिष्ट सराव आणि बैठकांची रचना विकसित केली ज्यामुळे लोक हे सुनिश्चित करतात की त्यांचे विधायक हेतू एकमेकांना सकारात्मकपणे अनुभवतात. सर्जनशील वर्तन साधनांचा वापर समक्रमणाचा  अनुप्रयोग शोध सत्रांच्या पलीकडे बऱ्याच परिस्थितींमध्ये वाढवितो (विशेषतः विवादाचे रचनात्मक निराकरण).

          गॉर्डन यांनी परिचितला विचित्र आणि विचित्र परिचित करण्यासाठी " रूपकात्मक प्रक्रियेचे " महत्त्व यावर जोर दिला . त्यांनी आपले केंद्रीय तत्व म्हणून व्यक्त केले: "परक्या गोष्टींवर विश्वास ठेवा आणि ज्या गोष्टींवर विश्वास ठेवला जाईल अशा गोष्टी दूर ठेवा." हा एक हात, मूलभूत समस्या-विश्लेषण, प्रोत्साहन आणि दुसरीकडे, दुरावलेपणा निर्मिती मूळे समस्या अशा प्रकारे नवीन आणि आश्चर्यकारक निराकरण बाहेर येणे शक्य आहे.

 

        एक शोध साधन म्हणून, समक्रमणाने सर्जनशील सुरुवातीच्या कल्पना मिळविण्यासाठी "स्प्रिंगबोर्डिंग" नावाचे तंत्र शोधले. सुरवातीची कल्पना विकसित होऊन आणखी वाढते. ही कल्पना विकासासाठी महत्त्वपूर्ण मूल्यांकन प्रक्रिया देखील जोडते, जी भ्रूणविषयक नवीन कल्पना घेते आणि ज्या आकर्षक आहेत परंतु अद्याप व्यवहार्य नाहीत , त्यांना अंमलात आणणाऱ्या लोकांची वचनबद्धता असलेल्या कार्यवाहीच्या नवीन कार्यप्रणाली बनवण्यात येत आहेत.

“वाबी-साबी” ही जपानी संस्कृतीत सौंदर्याची संकल्पना आहे जी ७०० वर्षांपूर्वी चीनमधून बौद्ध प्रभावाने विकसित झाली आणि आधुनिक संस्कृती आणि डिझाइनमध्ये अजूनही ती खोलवर रुजलेली “सौंदर्य” कल्पना आहे. “वाबी-साबी” या संकल्पनेचे दोन भाग आहेत. 

पहिला भाग, “वाबी” बहुतेकदा अडाणी साधेपणाशी संबंधित असतो आणि एखाद्या वस्तूचे खरे “सौंदर्य” परिपूर्ण करण्यासाठी आवश्यक अशा अनन्य दोषांचे प्रतिनिधित्व करतो, जसे की डागलेल्या काचेच्या खिडकीच्या पॅनमधील अपूर्णतेमुळे संपूर्ण प्रतिमेचे “सौंदर्य” वाढते. जेव्हा प्रकाश चमकतो. साबी हा परिधान आणि अश्रूंच्या माध्यमातून सौंदर्याचा अपरिहार्य क्षय आणि उत्क्रांतीचा संदर्भ देतो, जसे की लाकडी रेलिंगमुळे शेकडो हात आपले तेल मागे ठेवून मूळ लाकडाचे वार्निश विचलित करतात.

साध्या शब्दात सांगायचे तर , ”वाबी-साबी” कोणत्याही वस्तूच्या कमतरता व चंचलपणाचे “सौंदर्य” आहे.

 

आधुनिक अनुप्रयोग

 

          आधुनिक काळात, ”वाबी-साबी”ची कल्पना कलाकृतीपेक्षा बरेच काही हस्तांतरित केली जाऊ शकते. लिव्हिंग रूमच्या मजल्यावरील विखुरलेल्या लहान मुलाच्या खेळण्यांप्रमाणेच, आपल्या जीवनातील आनंद परिभाषित करणाऱ्या अंतर्भूत अपूर्णतांना आत्मसात करण्याविषयी,  त्यास मदत-सहाय्य मार्गदर्शकाचा विचार करते. आयुष्यातील “वाबी-साबी” एखाद्या व्यक्तीस केवळ अपूर्णतेस क्षमा करण्यास किंवा त्याकडे दुर्लक्ष करू नये असे सांगत नाही तर त्यास आपल्या स्वतःच्या सौंदर्याचा एक निर्णायक बिंदू म्हणून स्वीकारण्यास उत्तेजन देते आणि आपण सतत लुप्त होत असतो आणि बदलत असतो हे स्वतःस स्वीकारण्यास प्रवृत्त करते.

 

“वाबी-साबी” आणि भाषा

 

          “वाबी-साबी” भाषिक दृष्टीकोनातून मार्गदर्शन देखील देऊ शकते. भाषेच्या जागतिक उत्क्रांतीची दोन्ही पुरोगामी म्हणून स्तुती केली जाते आणि कधीही न संपणाऱ्या परंपरा आणि अद्वितीय संस्कृतींच्या संरचनेचे नुकसान म्हणून शोक व्यक्त केले जाते. तथापि, भाषांतर उद्योगात, आपण पाहतो की भाषेमधील बदल अटळ आहे. जागतिकीकरणामुळे एका भाषेला दुसऱ्या भाषेशी जोडण्यासाठी अधिकाधिक 'उधार शब्द' मिळू शकतात, भाषा स्वस्त होण्याऐवजी, एक समृद्ध बंधुत्व निर्माण होते जेव्हा वेगवेगळ्या जगातील दोन लोक एकाच कल्पनेस नैसर्गिकरित्या आणि अंतर्ज्ञानाने सामायिक करू शकतात.  जसजसे आपण सर्वजण एकमेकांजवळ येऊ लागतो तसतसे आपण आपल्यास वेगळे बनवणारे काहीतरी गमावू शकतो, परंतु कदाचित हे उत्सव अशा लोकांच्या जगामध्ये निर्माण झाले आहे जे एकमेकांना अधिक चांगले समजतात आणि जगाला थोडेसे अधिक म्हणून पाहतात पूर्वीपेक्षा एकजूट.

ते संवाद साधण्यासारखे ”वाबी-साबी”चे उदाहरण आहे .

 

          लेओनार्ड कोरेन च्या मते "आपण पारंपारिक जपानी “सौंदर्य” म्हणून काय वाटते याचे सर्वात उल्लेखनीय आणि वैशिष्ट्यपूर्ण वर्णन केले जाऊ शकते. जपानी त्याच ठिकाणी व्यापलेले देवता म्हणून सौंदर्याचे मूल्य तर ग्रीकमध्ये आदर्श “सौंदर्य” आणि पाश्चिमात्य देशांमध्ये परिपूर्णताशी संबंधित करताना असे नमूद केले आहे की, "एखादी वस्तू किंवा अभिव्यक्ती आपल्यामध्ये निर्मळ रोग आणि आध्यात्मिक उत्कटतेची भावना आणू शकली तर ती वस्तू वाबी-साबी असे म्हटले जाऊ शकते."  रिचर्ड पॉवेलसाठी, "वाबी-साबी तीन सोप्या गोष्टी ओळखून प्रामाणिक असलेल्या सर्व गोष्टींचे पालनपोषण करते: काहीही टिकत नाही, काहीही संपले नाही आणि काहीही परिपूर्ण नाही."

     

     वाबी आणि साबी शब्द सहज अनुवादित होत नाहीत. वाबीने मुळात निसर्गामध्ये राहून, समाजातून दुरावलेल्या एकाकीपणाचा उल्लेख केला. साबी म्हणजे "थंडगार", "दुबळे" किंवा "विरहित". चौदाव्या शतकाच्या उत्तरार्धात अधिक सकारात्मक अर्थ लावून हे अर्थ बदलू लागले.  वाबी आता देहाती साधेपणा, ताजेपणा किंवा शांतता यांचे प्रतिरूप आहे आणि ते नैसर्गिक आणि मानवनिर्मित वस्तू किंवा कमी प्रमाणात लालित्य दोन्हीवर लागू होऊ शकते. हे बांधकाम प्रक्रियेतून उद्भवणार्‍या क्वार्क्स आणि विसंगतींचा देखील संदर्भ घेऊ शकते, जे वस्तूमध्ये विशिष्टता आणि अभिजातपणा जोडतात. साबी हे “सौंदर्य” किंवा निर्मळपणा आहे जे वयानुसार येते जेव्हा वस्तूचे जीवन आणि तिचे सामर्थ्य यावर पुरावे दिले जातात.

 

          शतकानुशतके चीनच्या कलात्मक आणि बौद्ध प्रभावांचा समावेश करून, वाबी-साबी शेवटी एक जपानी आदर्श म्हणून विकसित झाली. कालांतराने, वाबी आणि साबीचे अर्थ अधिक हलकी व आशादायक बनले. काही वर्षांपूर्वी, विशेषत: जपानी खानदानी लोकांमध्ये शून्यता व अपूर्णता समजून ज्ञानप्राप्तीच्या पहिल्या चरणात त्यांना समान मानले गेले . आजच्या जपानमध्ये, वाबी-साबीचा अर्थ बर्‍याचदा "नैसर्गिक साधेपणामधील शहाणपणा" वर संक्षेप केला जातो. कलाविषयक पुस्तकांमध्ये हे सामान्यतः "सदोष “सौंदर्य”" म्हणून परिभाषित केले जाते.

 

     अभियांत्रिकी किंवा डिझाइनच्या दृष्टिकोनातून, वाबीचा अर्थ कोणत्याही वस्तूची अपूर्ण गुणवत्ता म्हणून ओळखला जाऊ शकतो, विशेषत: अंदाजित किंवा बदलत्या वापर अटींच्या संदर्भात डिझाइन आणि बांधकामात होईल. त्यानंतर साबीचा अर्थ अपूर्ण विश्वसनीयता किंवा कोणत्याही वस्तूचा मर्यादित मृत्यू हा पैशाच्या रूपात केला जाऊ शकतो

या मूर्तिमंत्याचे चांगले उदाहरण जपानी कुंभारांच्या विशिष्ट शैलींमध्ये दिसू शकते.  जपानी चहा समारंभमध्ये वापरलेली मातीची भांडी, अनेकदा अडाणी आणि साधी असतात.

 

     वाबी आणि साबी दोघेही निर्जनपणा आणि एकटेपणाच्या भावना सूचित करतात. महायान पंथामध्ये बौद्ध विश्वाचा दृश्य, भौतिक जगाशी संबंध नसणे आणि त्यापासून मुक्ती( सोपे जीवन ) याकडे प्रामुख्याने सकारात्मक वैशिष्ट्ये म्हणून पाहिले जाते . महायान तत्त्वज्ञान स्वतः चेतावणी देते की शब्द किंवा भाषेतून अस्सल समज प्राप्त होऊ शकत नाही, म्हणून अवास्तव अटींवर वाबी-साबी स्वीकारणे हा सर्वात योग्य दृष्टीकोन असू शकतो.

 

              सायमन ब्राउन अनावश्यक विचारात अडकण्याऐवजी वाबी-साबी अशा एका विधानाचे वर्णन करते, ज्याद्वारे विद्यार्थी इंद्रियांच्या माध्यमातून जीवन जगण्यास शिकू शकतात आणि आयुष्यात चांगलेच व्यस्त होऊ शकतात. या अर्थाने वाबी-साबी हे झेन बौद्ध धर्माचे भौतिक प्रतिनिधित्व आहे. अशी कल्पना आहे की नैसर्गिक, बदलत्या, अनन्य वस्तूंनी वेढल्या गेल्याने आपणाला आपल्या वास्तविक जगाशी जोडण्यास मदत होते आणि संभाव्य तणावपूर्ण विघटनापासून मुक्त होऊ शकतो.

 

        एका अर्थाने वाबी-साबी हे एक प्रशिक्षण आहे ज्यायोगे वाबी-साबीचा विद्यार्थी सर्वात मूलभूत, नैसर्गिक वस्तू मनोरंजक, मोहक आणि सुंदर पद्धतीने शोधणे शिकवते. शरद ऋतूत पाने लुप्त होणे हे एक उदाहरण आहे. फुलदाणीमधील चीर किंवा फुटलेला भाग त्याला अधिक मनोरंजक बनवते आणि वस्तूला अधिक ध्यानमूल्य दिले जाते त्या प्रमाणात वाबी-साबी जगाबद्दलची आपली धारणा बदलू शकते. उदा. लाकूड, कागद आणि फॅब्रिक यासारख्या सामग्रीमध्ये ते अधिक मनोरंजक बनतात कारण ते काळानुसार पाळल्या जाणार्‍या बदलांचे प्रदर्शन करतात.

निष्कर्ष

 

  • कलाकृती फक्त कौशल्य व कृतीचे प्रदर्शन नसून  ती मानवी मनावर भावनांची होणारी घालमेल किंवा त्याची प्रतिमा आहे.

​​​​​​​

  • कृती करण्यासाठी फक्त त्या अवयवास मेंदूद्वारे संदेश जातो. परंतु कलाकृती सादर करताना मन व सुप्त मन कार्यरत असते. कलाकृतीचा आशय जर कलाकाराच्या भावनांशी संवाद करत असेल तर कलाकृती सजीव घडत जाते.

​​​​​​​

  • ज्याप्रमाणे कलाकारास भावनांचा नियम लागू पडतो तसा कलारसिकासही तो लागु पडतो. कलाकृती रासिकांच्या मनात भावनिक कल्लोळ किंवा आनंददायक भाव निर्माण करते, आणि त्या चित्रात “सजीवता” जाणवते.

​​​​​​​

  • चित्रातील कौशल्य व व्यावसायिक पूर्णत्व या बाजूला ठेऊनही कलाकृतीचा आस्वाद घेता येतो. ते चित्र तांत्रिकदृष्ट्या व शास्त्रीयदृष्ट्या चुकीचे, अपूर्ण असू शकते  परंतु त्यातील पूर्णत्व जाणवते.

​​​​​​​

  • “भावना" हे सजीव असण्याचे सत्य आहे. चित्रकाराचे मन व रसिकांचे मन वेगळे बिंदू असतील तर त्यांना जोडणारी रेषा ही भावना असेल.

​​​​​​​

  • कला ही भावना व्यक्त करण्याचे साधन आहे. चित्रातील कौशल्य व त्याच्या तांत्रिक पूर्णतेपेक्षा चित्राचे “सौंदर्य” हे कलाकाराच्या भावना व्यक्त होण्यात आहे.

​​​​​​​

  • चित्राची मूलतत्त्वे जर कोणी मांडली नसती.किंवा ती अस्तित्वात आली नसती ,तेव्हा जे चित्र घडेल ते खूप बाजूने अपूर्ण असेल परंतु त्यात “सजीवता” व पूर्णत्व असेल.

​​​​​​​

  • चित्र पूर्ण असणे व चित्रात पूर्णत्व असणे या दोन खूप भिन्न गोष्टी आहेत. चित्र अभ्यासण्यापेक्षा अनुभवणे महत्त्वाचे आहे.

​​​​​​​

  • कलाकाराच्या भावना व चित्रात एक प्रकारचे समक्रमण असते जे त्याच्या चित्रात “सहजता” व “सजीवता” आणते.

 

     चित्राच्या सहजतेत त्याचे “सौंदर्य” आणि त्याच्या अपूर्णतेतही पूर्णत्व असते हा निष्कर्ष मिळतो.

fields.name_of_index: Portrayal of the Elephant King Chhadanta
fields.content:
The surviving remains of Indian art cover a period of more than two thousand years. During this time many schools of thought have flourished and decayed, invaders of many races have poured into India and contributed to the infinite variety of her intellectual resources; countless dynasties have ruled and passed away; and so we do not wonder that many varieties of artistic expression remain, to record for us, in a language of their own. Just as through all Indian schools of thought there runs like a golden thread the fundamental idealism of Upanishads, the Vedanta, so in all Indian art there is a unity that underlies all its different variations.[1]  Indian Art has its own style of narration of its own literature. Narration is in form of stories, poetry, dance, drama, paintings, sculpture etc. Indian narrative materials on which these paintings, sculpture, poetry are based on the mythological stories, depicting daily chores, also showing the cultural locality, tradition etc. Just as in poetry in the paintings to these narrative materials were artistically refined and just like poetry the art of paintings created clichés, on which the individual design of each artist are based on. The pictorial description needs just a few clichés to explain the scene in the paintings and events taking place in them to anyone familiar with the pictorial language. For one who is completely unfamiliar with it requires written or verbal explanation, just as one unaware of the language of poetry needs commentary.[2]

 

     The earliest paintings in India have been found in primitive caves and rock shelters. These paintings were mainly based on hunting scenes representing man in his encounter with wild animals.2 whereas the earliest historical paintings in India belong to the Satvahana period. The Satvahana were the most dominant power in the Deccan from the 2nd century B.C. to the 2nd century A.D. During the time of these monarchs, some of the most glorious Buddhist caves were excavated in living rocks. Mostly they were located in the western part of India that is Nasik, Bedsa, Bhaja, Karla, Kondane caves. The earliest caves at Ajanta are also from the Satvahana period. The fresco paintings of this period at Ajanta finely cover the walls, pillars and celling. Mostly this cave illustrates the scene from life of the Buddha and his previous lives as depicted in Jataka and Avadanas. The caves at Ajanta are covered with the depiction of floral, animal and decorative motifs.[3]  The Ajanta Satvahana period was followed by the Vakataka period. The Vakataka are first mentioned in inscriptions of 2nd century A.D. from Amravati. Some of the caves at Ajanta have inscriptions of the Vakataka period. The caves with more elaborated pillars and capitals are of the Vakataka period. It’s mainly the decorative element, chiefly composed of pearls and ribbons, so characteristic of the Vakataka age. This period tradition as seen at Ajanta is derived from earlier Satvahana. There are excellent illustrations in these paintings at Ajanta of six limbs of paintings, shadanga, composed of rupabheda, variety of form, pramana, proper proportion, bhava, depiction of emotion, lavanya yojana, infusion of grace, sadrishya, likeness and varnika bhanga, mixing of colours to produce a visual depth in the paintings. The diversity of form is indeed incredible. The artists have excellently painted a vast complex of human, animals and plant forms creating a drama. The artist at Ajanta has control over not only proportions of individual figures but also have ability to compose them.[4] Thus these frescos at Ajanta are also called as highly sophisticated art. The connection between the painting and dramatic technique is as close as that between the painting and the literature.[5]

 

     The narrative material on which the paintings at Ajanta belong in a superficial Buddhist revision. Artist depicts the hunting adventures, as well as travel adventures and even romantic scene. Also stories giving examples for both clever and ethical behaviour in general and especially on affairs of state and last but not the least Jataka tales. Caves are painted at all is due to the fact that sponsor who favour Buddhism wished to give monks the opportunity to impart their teaching to visitors of monasteries through the pictorial walls as well as through words. This purpose of monastery painting implicate that the theme of paintings were revised in Buddhist spirit and some were invented by the monk itself.[6] Thus the wall paintings mostly of Jataka stories are the pictorial sermon which imparts various teachings or parimitas by Buddha. There are around 550 Jataka tales that describes the event and pervious birth of Buddha, sometimes animal, sometimes as a human.[7] Many of the tales from Jataka are artistically composed on wall. As we know Jataka are stories about one of the incarnation of Buddha prior to his birth as prince Siddhartha, son of king Suddhodara and queen Maya. Jataka were extensively used to proclaim the massage of Buddha to the pilgrims. So the monks and the painted stone walls narrate the life and teaching of Buddha as in chhadanta Jataka, guru Jataka, kapi Jataka and lot more.[8] One of the interesting pictorial narrations of Jataka tale can be seen twice in Ajanta of Chhadanta Jataka. Chhadanta Jataka has several versions of stories. Where Chhadanta literally mean six tusks or six teeth. This story mainly depicts the Dana parimita of the bodhisattva. The most common narration of this Jataka is like:-

Figure 1 – Chhadanta Jataka Cave No 17

“ Far away in the Himalaya on blue waters of Chhadantadaho lake, protected by the seven rock ranges, in a deep cave, dwelt bodhisattva, king of 8000 Chhadanta elephant with his two elephant queen. It chanced on a day that two queen were standing under a large banyan tree, which the king having shaken, Mahasubhadra , the elder, was showered over with golden dust from the flowers while on Challusubhadra, the younger, fell dry sticks, leaves and ants. Jealousy of Mahasubhadra, and hatred of the king filled chullasubhadra’s breast and she prayed that in her next birth she might become Subadra, daughter of king of Madu and wed the king of Banares. Him she would beguile in to sending a hunter to slay the king of elephants, conspicuous from his white body, red mouth and feet, and six tusks and killed herself and was born as she wished to be. She remembered her old jealousy and in due time the royal hunter Sonuttara was sent to kill the king of elephants, Subadra giving him full directions as to the route he should follow the suvarna hills, above the Chhadantadaho lake. Whence the Sonuttara would easily recognise the great white king. Surrounded by his herd of elephants, under the spreading banyan tree. From his rocky height he observed the king going daily after bathing, to a retired spot and here the hunter dug a pit and wrapping himself in a saffron robe of a priest, waited for favourable moment and shot who sought to pacify him by spreading the sacred robe over his trunk. Questioning the hunter, the bodhisattva ascertains that he is doing subhadra’s bidding, where upon he cuts off his tusk himself and offers them in his trunks. The hunter returned from his murderous errand; and laying the tusk before the queen he said ‘Respected queen, in your previous birth having cherished hatred against your husband the king of the Chhadanta elephant you wished to kill him. Accordingly I have killed him and here are his tusks.’ The queen filled with remorse for her cruel deed in causing the death of such a noble animal, she died the same day of a broken heart.”[9]

 

Figure 2 – Detail drawing of the mural of Chhadanta Jataka from Cave No 17

 

The visual narration of this Chhadanta Jataka is painted in two caves, cave no. 10 and cave no. 17. The painting in cave 17 has a different narrative pattern. The mural is damaged and remained in fragments.[10] This Chhadanta Jataka mural is located at the left side of the entrance door of cave 17. The size of the mural is around 10ft. 3in. by 10ft. 3in. The pictorial narrative pattern is aligned or ordered. It seems to be scattered in a way. The artist had made changes as per the space. One without knowing the Jataka cannot identify the visual narration of the tale. Taking sense in order in which they occur in the story, the Chhadanta elephants are shown in the lower part of the composition among the lotus plants and other tropical vegetation. Number of ants is shown climbing the stem. Two hill people, a man and a woman are up in the rocks, the man carries a bow and arrows in his right hand, and dagger in his waist-belt, woman has three rows of beads round the waist, to which a bunch of leaves is attached, watching the white elephant below, on the back of which a wolf has leapt. To the right two black faced monkeys (langur) and below them two vultures sit on the rocks.[11] Which shows that the inhabitants of jungle watch a wolf and vultures near the queen elephant Challusubhadra, who leapt down from the rocks to her death.[12] At the top left-hand corner, the king is shown seated on a couch, which his queen reclining against him. Both appear happy. Two men approach them on their knees, which seem to have brought news of importance probably of the Chhadanta elephant. At the top centre of the picture a man is shown in act of discharging his bow at the elephant below.[13] In the top right corner, a seated devotee with an elephant is shown; whose trunk is raised may be Challusubhadra worshipping a prateyka Buddha in the mountains to ensure herself a good incarnation.[14] In the right centre of the picture stands the huge white elephant king, Chhadanta, with only one tusk, upon which he rests his trunk under a jewelled tree, while a man, hunter kneels and makes profound obeisance before him. The same hunter is shown carry away the tusks, slung on sticks across their shoulders. He is the hunter of the legend, and from his dress and short spares beards, looks like the jungle man. Above it is a herd of elephants, both large and small, in a state of great excitement. To the left is the final scene of this visual Jataka story. In a pavilion of the palace, the king sits on a couch, and supports the queen, who stricken with remorse , in causing, as she imagined, the death of the elephant king Chhadanta, mourns in her husband’s arms. A dark skinned female attendant looks wistfully in to her face; while beside, others are engaged in fanning and using fly flap. At the foot of the couch, a woman kneels and brushes the queen’s feet with a lotus flower, while another is engaged in picking rice, as she has before the common bamboo winnowing basket used by natives for cleaning grain. Above, a servant, in a white tunic bound round the waist with a belt, enters with a tray containing the two elephant tusk, which he is about to present to the queen. Two men behind are engaged in conversation. The upper part of the pavilion is richly decorated by festoons.[15]

 

     Although the visual narration has many changes in the story than that of the real Jataka story, still it completely narrates the story of elephant king Chhadanta showing his greatness and teaching of the bodhisattva of Dana parimita. The visual narrative compositions are scattered on the wall but it still justice to the story. The repetition of the characters helps in the narration. The viewer can completely understand the Jataka painting of king Chhadanta with the verbal interpretations. The painting style and the compositions with the shadanga make the painting more beautiful. Various scenes in the painting generate a curiosity in viewer about the story and starts composing the Jataka with the repetitive forms and figures. Although the Chhadanta king is with two tusks his greatness is shown using the semi-realistic herd of elephants and jewelled tree behind him showing the vegetation of the jungle. The hunter is shown in various actions firstly he kneels down before the elephant king, then casts a reverent glance at the elephant and lastly goes to the royal court with tusks, this shows the repetition of the hunter in the painting like in the story board. So the visual narration and composition of the mural painting in cave no. 17 of one of the birth of Buddha as Chhadanta king completely narrates the story in a very alluring way.
